questiontext.text:
Exercise

As a real number \(x\) approaches zero we note hiigher powers of  \(x\) become even closer to zero and may even fall within a margin of error we can tolerate. 

Assume, for this exercise, that \(x^3\) and higher powers may be ignored in comparison to lower order terms.

Find a quadratic polynomial approximating \( (1−x)^{{@pp@}} \). Hint: First expand \( (1+x)^{{@pp@}} \) using the binomial series with \(p=\displaystyle{@pp@} \)and with \( x \) replaced by \( (−x) \):

\( (1-x)^{@pp@} \approx \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]

generalfeedback.text:
The binomial series gives \[ (x-1)^{@pp@} \approx {@ta@}.\]

What we have done in this exercise is to approximate the function \((1-x)^{{@pp@}}\) by the simpler (polynomial) function \(\displaystyle {@ta@}\) which is reasonable provided \(x\) is very small. 

In the case of \((1-x)^{\frac{1}{2}}\)this approximation is well illustrated geometrically by drawing the curves \(y=(1-x)^{\frac{1}{2}}\) and \(y=1-\dfrac{1}{2}x-\dfrac{1}{8}x^2\). The two curves coincide when \(x\) is ‘small’.
